# Multiagent Workflow and Modular Code (Always Follow)

This repo is actively worked on by **multiple concurrent agents** (Cursor, Codex, Claude, and parallel sessions of each). Every chat MUST adhere to the following at all times, without being asked.

## Multiagent Workflow (mandatory)

1. **Always branch from fresh `main`.** Never commit directly to `main` unless the user explicitly requests a `main` hotfix. Follow `.cursor/rules/git-pr-workflow-default.mdc` strictly:
   - `git fetch origin`, base the work branch on `origin/main` (e.g. `git checkout -b agent/<slug> origin/main`).
   - One branch per task or agent stream; do **not** reuse another agent's in-flight branch.
   - Choose a **distinctive slug** (include the session topic plus a short nonce like `-kj1` if the topic is generic) so parallel agents never clash on branch name.
2. **Check for conflicts/clashes before opening the PR and before merging.**
   - Before pushing: `git fetch origin && git diff origin/main...HEAD --stat` and rebase/merge `origin/main` in if it has moved.
   - Inspect overlapping files against other active `agent/*` / `feat/*` / `fix/*` branches (e.g. `git log origin/agent/* --oneline --name-only`) and call out clashes in the PR body.
   - If another agent has pushed to the branch name you picked, assume collision: move your work to a new branch (`git checkout -b agent/<slug>-v2 origin/main`) and reapply.
   - Resolve conflicts deliberately — do not blindly accept either side. Preserve both agents' intent where possible.
3. **Respond to CI and PR review feedback, always.** After push and PR creation:
   - Watch PR checks (`gh pr checks <num> --watch`) and the Cloudflare deploy, not just local tests.
   - For every failure, read the log, fix on the same branch, push again. Loop until CI is green.
   - **PR review bots** are **peer reviewers**: address every automated review thread completely (fix, justify, or explicitly resolve) **before** squash-merge to **`main`**. Do not merge past unresolved bot feedback; see `.cursor/rules/git-pr-workflow-default.mdc` (“PR review bots”).
   - For human review comments, same standard: address each thread; do not ignore.
4. **Complete the production closeout** from `.cursor/rules/every-chat-commit-deploy-verify-production.mdc` **after** merge and Cloudflare deploy — never treat a green PR alone as shipped.
5. **Keep the Git graph readable:** after your PR merges, run **`npm run git:graph-hygiene`** (and delete the finished topic branch locally when safe). Prefer **Automatically delete head branches** on GitHub and avoid extra local branch names pointing at the same commit as **`main`** unless a **worktree** forces it. See `docs/CONCURRENT_AGENT_WORKFLOW.md` (“Keeping the Git graph readable”).

## Modular Code (mandatory)

LLMs have finite context windows; large files cause subtle breakage when agents edit them. Keep code modular so any agent can safely load a whole file.

- **Hard ceiling: 1000 lines per file.** Files at or above this MUST be split before adding more code.
- **Soft target: 800 lines or less.** When a file crosses 800 LOC in a change, plan a split in the same PR or file a follow-up in `docs/REFACTOR_BACKLOG.md`.
- **Also cap functions at ~50 lines** and avoid duplicated logic in 3+ places (extract a helper).
- Apply the split along **natural seams** (domain concerns, lifecycle stages, UI section, data source, etc.), not arbitrary line counts. Preserve public API; update imports; keep behaviour identical unless the task asks otherwise.
- Exemptions (do not refactor purely for size): `wrangler.toml`, `wrangler.jsonc`, `tsconfig*.json`, `vite.config.*`, `vitest.config.*`, `package.json`, `package-lock.json`, generated files, D1 migrations, real-data test fixtures (per `.cursor/rules/no-mock-test-data.mdc`), `node_modules`, build output, `.env*`.
- When editing any file, proactively check its size. If it is over 800 LOC and the change is non-trivial, extract a module as part of the same work or add it to the backlog.

## Enduring scope

These rules apply in **every chat, past and future, without being reminded**. They override any default assumption that a single large file, a shared branch, or ignoring CI is acceptable.
